{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"90507976-586f-4a34-8abb-59aeb4cd373a","content":"`SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` only tells the **page** not to add padding for safe areas. You likely also need to address the navigation chrome and ensure the layout fills the available space:\n\n**1. Hide Shell/NavigationPage chrome** (if applicable):\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage\n    Shell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\"\n    Shell.TabBarIsVisible=\"False\"\n    SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"\n    Padding=\"0\">\n```\n\n**2. Ensure the Image fills the layout:**\n\n```xml\n<Image Source=\"photo.jpg\"\n       Aspect=\"AspectFill\"\n       HorizontalOptions=\"Fill\"\n       VerticalOptions=\"Fill\" />\n```\n\n**3. On Android**, if targeting below Android 15, you may need to explicitly opt into edge-to-edge in `MainActivity.cs`:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)\n{\n    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);\n    AndroidX.Core.View.WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window, false);\n}\n```\n\nOn Android 15+ (API 35), edge-to-edge is enforced automatically, so `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` alone should suffice.\n\n**Most common culprit:** Shell or NavigationPage still rendering its nav bar, which constrains the page below the status bar. Setting `Shell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\"` usually resolves the remaining gap.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7b528260-a179-4492-b342-6a1deafdc592","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making content go edge-to-edge in a .NET MAUI app targeting .NET 10, specifically wanting an image to fill the entire screen behind the status bar and navigation bar. They've tried `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the ContentPage but still see padding.\n\nThis is a question about .NET MAUI's safe area/edge-to-edge APIs. Let me think about what I know and whether I need to search for information.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, to achieve edge-to-edge content that goes behind system bars, you typically need to:\n\n1. Ignore safe area insets - which they're trying with `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"`\n\n\n2. But there might be additional steps needed depending on the platform\n\nFor .NET 10 specifically, Android enforces edge-to-edge by default following Android 15's requirements, so `SafeAreaEdges` alone might not be the complete solution. I should consider whether they need to use `IgnoreSafeArea` on individual views, or if there are platform-specific configurations needed for both Android and iOS to truly extend content behind the system bars.\n\nThe real issue could be that Shell or NavigationPage is adding its own chrome on top of the page layout, or on Android specifically, the framework might still be applying window insets even with edge-to-edge enabled. Let me think through what's most likely causing the problem—whether it's navigation chrome, platform-specific inset handling, or a combination of these factors. default but `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust` and insets handling matter\n\nThe most common issue when `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` doesn't work is:\n- On Android: The page might still be laid out within the system bar area because of how the Android activity handles window insets\n- The `Padding` property on the page might be set\n- The parent container (Shell, NavigationPage) might be constraining the layout\n\nFor .NET MAUI targeting .NET 10, the likely answer involves:\n\n1. Setting `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` (which they already did) - this is correct for iOS\n2. On Android, ensuring edge-to-edge is properly configured. In .NET 9+/10, Android edge-to-edge is opt-in or automatic depending on target SDK. You might need to set the status bar and navigation bar to transparent.\n3. Making sure the image uses `Aspect=\"AspectFill\"` to actually fill the space\n4. Potentially using `Shell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\"` if in Shell\n\nIn .NET 9+, `SafeAreaEdges` controls padding to avoid system UI overlap, but on Android the system bars also need to be transparent for content to render behind them. For .NET 10 with Android 15+, edge-to-edge is enforced, so the bars should be transparent automatically—but if it's still not working, I'm thinking the issue might be Shell adding its own padding or the page itself having padding constraints that's preventing the full extension. The core issue is likely that `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` isn't being applied correctly or there's a platform-specific override happening—I should focus on the practical steps: removing any page padding, disabling Shell navigation elements if present, ensuring the Image fills the entire space, and potentially adding platform-specific code to handle Android's system bar behavior in .NET 10.","outputTokens":1879,"requestId":"502E:E9FEE:1C90831:1FB61F8:69FA92AB"},"id":"32a5bb1a-68d2-4f20-b0c9-46311f905c09","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:01:05.947Z","parentId":"fbd57dc3-b864-4c3f-b43d-906d57924873"}
